Boston is a dataset containing information about the housing situation of Boston, including things like crime rates, accessibility to highways and median value of occupied homes. 

pairs(Boston)

cor_matrix<-cor(Boston)
corrplot(cor_matrix, method="square", type="upper", cl.pos="b", tl.pos="d")

It looks like age corresponds strongly with living in more industrial areas, which of course have significantly more nitrogen oxide in the air. Correlation between lstat and rm also imply that lower status people are more likely to live in dwellings with more rooms, which is backed by a strong negative correlation between dwellings with lots of rooms and median value of owner-occupied homes.

boston_scaled<- as.data.frame(boston_scaled)
bins<-quantile(boston_scaled$crim)
bb<-c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high")
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label=bb)
#table(crime)
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)
n<-nrow(boston_scaled)
ind<-sample(n, size=n*0.8)
train<-boston_scaled[ind,]
test<-boston_scaled[-ind,]
correct_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)
lda.fit <- lda(crime~., data = train)
#lda.fit
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col=classes, pch=classes)

#For some reason the data is reversed on the x-axis compared to the datacamp plot, I went through the whole code and couldn't find why

As we can see, the predict function was quite good at predicting crime rates overall, particularly high crime rates. This would imply that high crime rates exhibit a certain tell that the LDA uses to predict with high accuracy. The low, med_low and med_high categories seem to be quite easily separated from the high-category.

2 clusters seems to be what brings most change, making it the optimal number. This graph has grouped the data in the scaled bos-table into 2 clusters, and then maps that data according to the stated categories. It appears to have divided dwellings largely based on whether theyre in an industrial area (with a high nitrogen oxide concentration) or not, and so we can use the graph to figure out what things correspond or dont correspond with living in an industrial area, like for example that people living in those areas generally have a lower tax rate. The data represents basic human development metrics such as life expectancy and average education, and shows relationships between these variables. The plots show us, among other things, that countries with many adolescent births also have significantly higher maternal mortality rates and lower life expectancies, and that countries where women receive more similar levels of education to men generally have better education as a whole and dont have as many adolescent births. The better educated countries with higher life expectancies also have higher GNIs per capita, which can probably be expected.

This result is much more interpretable and shows clear correlations between life expectancy, education and GNI, female representation in parliament and employment rate between genders and between adolescent birth rate and maternal mortality rate. The last group is almost directly opposite the first, meaning that they correlate inversely with each other, but the 2nd group is orthogonal to the other two, meaning that they have no correlation. Knowing this we can easily choose 2 principal components to represent the data.

The results between the 2 graphs are different because it assumes that variables with larger variance are more important than those with small variance, so scaling the data is necessary to prevent a few categories from dominating the results.

Since life expectancy correlates strongly with education and gross national income and inversely with adolescent birth rates and maternal mortality ratios, we can use it as the first PC. Employment rate between genders and female representation in parliament dont correlate all that strongly, but theyre both quite orthogonal to the other variables as well, so Id choose one of them for the second PC

From the graph we can see that tea shops often serve their tea unpackaged, while chain stores tend to use tea bags, and tea shop+chain store combinations do both. Green tea drinkers dont seem to have any other constant preferences, since green tea is not near any other variables. A lot of the most common variables such as sugar, no sugar, earl grey and not lunch are near each other, showing that they tend to appeal to the average user in a similar way. The other category is also very lonely, meaning that drinkers of that kind are quite unusual compared to the average tea enthusiasts, though the sample size might be too low to say anything definitive.

#This plot shows us that groups 2 and 3 have seen an increase in weight on average, while the rats in group 1 grew noticeably less. All the rats in these two groups started growing significantly faster around day 43-44, and their growth had either stagnated or started regressing before then.

Next we will standardise the values to highlight how rats that started out bigger will generally be bigger than the others throughout the study.

RATSL<-RATSL%>%

Now we are going to perform a two-sample t-test to get an accurate assesment of how the groups develop. Since our data has 3 samples, we have to exclude one. 

tgroup1<-RATSL8S1%>%
  filter(mean<460)
#Group 3 has all the biggest rats, so we can limit groups to 2 by limiting mean to a certain number, in this case 460. Groups 2 and 3 looked very similar, which is why 1 and 2 were chosen for the t-test.
t.test(mean ~ Group, data = tgroup1, var.equal = TRUE)
##
